snippet: The unexpectedly strong showing of the Svoboda party in recent parliamentary voting stirs concerns about the rise of xenophobia and anti-Semitism in Ukraine.
abstract: Oleg Tyagnibok, Ukrainian ultra-nationalist who was kicked out of Parliament in 2004 for his extreme views, is preparing to return as leader of Svoboda, right-wing party that has gained control of 8.5 percent of legislature after Oct 29 election; party's strong showing has stirred concerns about rise of xenophobia and anti-Semitism in Ukraine.
lead_paragraph: The unexpectedly strong showing of the Svoboda party in recent parliamentary voting stirs concerns about the rise of xenophobia and anti-Semitism in Ukraine.

headline.seo: Ukraine’s Ultranationalists Do Well in Elections
headline.main: Ukraine’s Ultranationalists Show Surprising Strength at Polls
headline.print_headline: Ukraine’s Ultranationalists Show Surprising Strength at Polls
